INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7cc824e4-68da-4c6e-8c00-08b11e32965c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kotlin: Mastering Build Variants with Gradle$escape$,
  $escape$In Kotlin Android projects, build variants are crucial for managing different configurations. You can create multiple product flavors and build types using the `productFlavors` and `buildTypes` blocks in the `build.gradle` file. For example, you can create a `free` and `pro` flavor with different values in the `android.defaultConfig.applicationId` property:

android {
    productFlavors {
        free {
            defaultConfig {
                applicationId 'com.example.free'
            }
        }
        pro {
            defaultConfig {
                applicationId 'com.example.pro'
            }
        }
    }
}

You can then use the `buildTypes` block to define different build types, such as `debug` and `release`:

android {
    buildTypes {
        debug {
            debuggable true
        }
        release {
            minifyEnabled true
            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile('proguard-android.txt'), 'proguard-rules.pro'
        }
    }
}

To use a specific build variant, you can use the `variant` property in the `build.gradle` file.$escape$,
  $escape$android {
    productFlavors {
        free {
            defaultConfig {
                applicationId 'com.example.free'
            }
        }
        pro {
            defaultConfig {
                applicationId 'com.example.pro'
            }
        }
    }

    buildTypes {
        debug {
            debuggable true
        }
        release {
            minifyEnabled true
            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile('proguard-android.txt'), 'proguard-rules.pro'
        }
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
